Note for usage of CHAN mode:
  Switcher task, after processing the last picture of a channel,
  will set channel mode to CHAN_RETIRED.

  Output task, after finish sending a picture, will check if this is the
  last picture of a channel with CHAN_RETIRED mode.  If so, will change
  channel mode to CHAN_NOT_USED.

  With old API, the Splice Request task will first check the mode of the
  new channel to make sure it is of CHAN_NOT_USED mode, then it will change
  the mode to CHAN_BG_OFF, before sending a splice request to Splice Control
  task.

  With new API, PPC will send SET_PIDGRP_REQ message to Control task.
  Control task will make sure the new channel is of CHAN_NOT_USED.
  If not, NAK will be sent back to PPC.  Otherwise, Control task will
  change the channel mode to CHAN_BG_OFF.  At the time of switch, PPC will
  send the SWITCH_REQUEST message to Control task.  Control task will
  signal the Splice Control task.

  Splice Control task will make sure the new channel is of CHAN_BG_OFF mode.
  It will then change the mode to CHAN_BG_SPLICE.
 

9/3/99
  New approach to support SeaChange API:
    - Use the PPC to generate the return switch request, immediately after
      it receives the indication of the first switch.  This way, the DPI
      can maintain the one switch for one request assumption.
    - Defines only the simpliest and core API between PPC and DSP.  Any
      mapping of more complicated API from venders should be done in the
      PPC side.
    - New functionality/API required between PPC/DSP to support SeaChange API:
      - switch based on frame count instead of switch time
      - cancellation of previous switch request
      - efficient way to support early switch request

  - Support of frame-based switch
      Frame-based switch is defined as switch on or after a specified frame
      number of the FG channel.  A new element, Int32 spliceFrm, will be added
      to ChanInfo.  Setting of spliceFrm to 0 or positive means frame-based
      switching.  When the outPicCnt >= spliceFrm, spliceTime will be set
      to the PET of this frame.  This checking will be done in FG_SPLICE
      mode.  SpliceTime of corresponding BG channel should also be set
      appropriately (TBD) to avoid losing the entry frame.

  - Support of cancellation of previous switch request
      This should be done by the Switcher task.  A SWITCH_CANCEL command
      should be received by the Switcher.  If everything is OK (correct
      FG and BG modes, switch not performed yet), the FG channel will be
      reset to FG_ON mode, with its picQue clean up.  The BG channel will
      be cleaned also, and mode returned to BG_OFF (or should it be NOT_USED).
      The cancel just cancel the switch request, not the BG channel, or should
      it be so?
      May be we can include a parameter in the cancel command to indicate
      whether BG channel should also be freed.

  - Efficient way to support early switch request
      In this case, we need to have an additional parameter, acqTime,
      for each channel.  This parameter indicates the acquire time for
      the channel, and should be specified in the setPidGrp command.
      If a switch request is received whose spliceTime or spliceFrm indicates
      that it is much more than the acqTime, then the FG channel will be
      put to a new mode, FG_SCHEDULED, while BG channel will remain in BG_OFF
      (instead of BG_SPLICE) mode.  When the splice time is about acqTime
      ahead, FG will change to FG_SPLICE, and BG will change to BG_SPLICE.
  ----------      

  - Improved Monitor Task.

  - Detailed API
      SWITCH_PIDGRP_REQ <-> DEL_PIDGRP: register and unregister channels
      START_PIDGRP <-> STOP_PIDGRP:     start and stop channel service
      SWITCH_CANCEL_REQ: only cancel splice request, will not unregister
                         BG channel
      Also, after a switch, old channel will not automatically be unregistered.
      As a result, it can be switched back without another setPidGrp.

  - Revised version of channel mode usage:
      Set Live PidGrp:   FG: NOT_USED -> FG_OFF
      Start Live PidGrp: FG: FG_OFF -> FG_ON
      Stop Live PidGrp:  FG: FG_ON -> FG_OFF
      Del Live PidGrp:   FG: FG_OFF -> NOT_USED

      Set Ad PidGrp:     BG: NOT_USED -> BG_OFF
      Splice Req:	 FG: FG_ON -> FG_SPLICE
                         BG: BG_OFF -> BG_SPLICE

      switcher done:     old FG: FG_SPLICE -> FG_FINISHING
                         old BG: BG_SPLICE -> FG_ON

      output done:       old FG: FG_FINISHING -> BG_OFF

      Del old PidGrp:    old FG: BG_OFF -> NOT_USED

      Splice cancel:     FG: FG_SPLICE -> FG_ON
                         BG: BG_SPLICE -> BG_OFF

  - Due to PPC concern, set PidGrp will automatically start PidGrp also.
    In the future, when dynamic grooming is used, we can even simplify
    the above approach:
      Set PidGrp:     NOT_USED -> OFF
      Start PidGrp:   OFF -> ON
      Stop PidGrp:    ON -> OFF
      Del PidGrp:     OFF -> NOT_USED

      Splice Req:     FG: ON -> FG_SPLICE
                      BG: OFF -> BG_SPLICE
                     (BG: OFF -> NAPPING -> BG_SPLICE with early switch support)

      switcher done:  old FG: FG_SPLICE -> FINISHING
                      old BG: BG_SPLICE -> STARTING

      new GOP found:  new FG: STARTING -> ON

      output:         old FG: FINISHING -> OFF

      Splice cancel:  FG: FG_SPLICE -> ON
                      BG: BG_SPLICE -> OFF

    Bufferer will process TPs of the following channel modes:
        ON, FG_SPLICE, BG_SPLICE, STARTING.

    Bufferer will ignore TPs of the following channel modes:
        NOT_USED, OFF, NAPPING, FINISHING


